question:
Type I error and Type II error

Methods for hypothesis testing are more than just a calculation exercise, the conclusions are intended to help people make real decisions about the subject of the analysis.

Using an example that we have discussed in class (or lab or homework), write a few sentences that:

· describe the null and alternative hypotheses for the chosen example;
· explain the meaning of a type 1 error (i.e., a "false positive") in the chosen context;
· explain the meaning of a type 2 error (i.e., a "false negative") in the chosen context;
· describe the potential consequences associated with each type of wrong decision (i.e., type 1 or type 2 error).

